Before addressing the remarkable gulf that separates heterodox economics
 and geographical political economy, some preliminary remarks about the
 two sides of the divide will be helpful, not only to identify them but
 also to demonstrate how remarkable it is that they are so isolated from
 each other and, perhaps, to shed some light on the reasons for their isolation.
 Economics and geography are both academic disciplines, and heterodox economics
 and geographical political economy both represent subsets within their
 respective disciplines.
 Nonetheless, their composition and situations are dissimilar.
